GNU Utilities Status and Task List

How to contribute

For all utilities except those for which I say "don't bother" below,
a program that runs on 4.2 is satisfactory as a contribution.
Programs written for other Unix versions are probably ok too.  I
expect porting to 4.2, which is what I use for debugging, would not
be too hard.  It is not certain how compatible the GNU kernel and
libraries will be with 4.2, so for now contributors might as well
refrain from worrying about this except for sticking to the highest
level 4.2 interfaces they can use (for example, if you look
at a directory, use readdir).

Contributed code should use dynamic allocation to avoid arbitrary
limits on the length or number of ANY data structure, including
filenames, lines, files, and symbols.  All system calls should be
checked for failure and the system error code should be printed;
failing mallocs should be detected.  When static storage is to
be written in during program execution it is cleaner to initialize
it by explicit code rather than by C initialized declarations.

Please do not read the source of the Unix original you are imitating.

Please supply a man file (or, even better, a texinfo file) with the
utility, since GNU cannot use the Unix manual itself.  Try to write
in a less terse style than the Unix manual and spell out important
conclusions and techniques that the Unix manual would leave to the
reader to deduce.

If the Unix manual mentions deficiencies for the utility you are
imitating, give a thought to removing those deficiencies in your
program.


