    But any network you would like to implement would be welcome.

If something is "available" it means it is possible to distribute with
GNU the same program that is used with Unix, so there is no need to
write a replacement.

If something "may be available" it means that there is a possibility
that the existing version can be used but also a possibility that
one must be written.  If you can find out for certain whether
any of these programs is available (by asking the author or
distributor), that is a useful contribution.  Alternatively,
if you are burning to write a replacement for a program even
though the original might be available, that is fine.

If something is "not needed", this does not mean it would be rejected
as a contribution if offered.

